/************************************************************************
 *			IMPORTANT NOTE					*
 ************************************************************************
 * If this language is changed, or if the instruction codes are		*
 * changed, BYTE_CODE_VERSION in evaluate/evaluate.h should be 		*
 * changed as well.							*
 ************************************************************************/

*************************************************************************
*			PROGRAM FORMAT					*
*************************************************************************

This describes the overall format of a package, in the language of 
this abstract machine.  What is described here is the external format,
which is used in a .aso file.  There is a corresponding internal format,
stored in memory while the interpreter is running.

Generally, the internal format 

   :: omits declarations

   :: replaces local labels in instructions (such as GOTO_I instructions)
      by their offsets from the address of the current instruction

   :: follows each environment size byte for a local environment by 
      three bytes giving the number of the environment descriptor for
      that environment.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

		ADDING INSTRUCTIONS
                -------------------

If an instruction is added, be sure to do the following modifications

 :: evaluate/instruct.h
      Define instruction number.  

 :: evaluate/evaluate.c
      Handle the evaluation of the instruction.

If this instruction does not follow a prefix instruction:

 :: evaluate/instinfo.c
      Add a line for new instruction in instinfo, providing
      information about the instruction.

 :: messages/instname.txt
      Add a line for the new instruction, if it is not something that
      follows a prefix instruction.

If this instruction follows UNARY_PREF_I:

 :: messages/unname.txt
      If the new instruction follows UNARY_PREF_I, then add a line
      to this file.

If this instruction follows BINARY_PREF_I:

 :: messages/binname.txt
      If the new instruction follows BINARY_PREF_I, then add a line
      to this file.

If this instruction follows any of the other prefix instructions

 :: evaluate/instinfo.c
      Add a line to an appropriate array giving instruction name.


Recompile disassemble.c.


=========================================================================
			PACKAGE
=========================================================================

A package consists of a sequence of bytes:

	(1) A header, consisting of the null-terminated string "ACODE" 
	    followed by three null-terminated strings:

	     (a) The byte code version (BYTE_CODE_VERSION) in decimal,

	     (b) The name of the package.  If there
		 are separate interface and implementation packages,
		 then this string is the name of the interface
		 package.  Otherwise, this string is the name of
		 the package.

	     (c) The name of the implementation package,
		 if there are separate interface and implementation
		 packages.  Otherwise, this string is empty
		 (so there are two null characters in a row).

	(2) A sequence of declarations, as described below.
	
	(3) A byte containing constant STOP_PACKAGE_I.

#########################################################################
			DECLARATIONS
#########################################################################

Each declaration has an internal form and an external form.

=========================================================================
			LABEL DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

Declaration LABEL_DCL_I(n) labels the next declaration n.  It is used for
giving names to constants and symbols that are declared.  n is one byte
long.  LONG_LABEL_DCL_I(n) is the same, but n is three bytes long, so more
labels can be used.

LABEL_DCL_I and LONG_LABEL_DCL_I do not have an internal form.

=========================================================================
			GENERAL ID DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

If s is a null-terminated string, then 

	NAME_DCL_I s

declares identifier s.  This instruction should be preceded by a label
instruction, and identifier s is refered to by that label.  

In the internal form, identifier s is put into the name array
for names that have no particular affiliation, 
and its index in that array is stored, as a three 
byte quantity, where the ID_DCL_I instruction occurs.

=========================================================================
			ENTITY ID DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

If s is a null-terminated string, then 

	ID_DCL_I s

declares identifier s.  This instruction should be preceded by a label
instruction, and identifier s is refered to by that label.  

In the internal form, identifier s is put into the entity id array 
(outer_binding) and its index in that array is stored, as a three 
byte quantity, where the ID_DCL_I instruction occurs.  Use the 
label to find that index.  (See GET_GLOBAL_I and FETCH_GLOBAL_I below.)

=========================================================================
			CONSTANT DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

A constant is placed in the package by one of the following declarations.
In each case, s is a null-terminated string.  In the case of STRING_DCL_I,
n is a 3 byte quantity giving the length of the string.

	STRING_DCL_I n s -- declare a string constant.
	INT_DCL_I    s  -- declare an integer constant (where s is its string
			   representation).
	REAL_DCL_I   s  -- declare a real/rational constant (where s is 
			   its string representation).

Each of these instructions should be preceded by a label.  The 
internal form stores the constant in an array of constants, and
stores the index in that array (as a three-byte integer) 
at the offset in the package where the constant declaration occurs.  
Use the label that precedes the constant declaration to find
that index.  See CONST_I below.

=========================================================================
			BEGIN/END EXTENSION DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

BEGIN_EXTENSION_DCL_I indicates the beginning of an extension.
END_EXTENSION_DCL_I indicates the end of an extension.  Declarations
that alter the genus/community hierarchy, or that create new
genera, communities, species or families only occur inside 
extensions.

When an END_EXTENSION_DCL_I is processed, the tables describing
the hierarchy are updated, if necessary.

=========================================================================
			GENUS, SPECIES, ETC. DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

Species, genus, etc. identifiers are declared by the following declarations.
s is the null-terminated identifier.  The instructions that start with
NEW create new ones, and the others refer to existing ones.

	SPECIES_DCL_I			s
        NEW_SPECIES_DCL_I		s	  -- s names a species, 

	FAMILY_DCL_I			s
	NEW_TRANSPARENT_FAMILY_DCL_I	s
	NEW_OPAQUE_FAMILY_DCL_I		s	  -- s names a family, 
				     		     (or is PAIR@ or 
						      FUNCTION@)

	GENUS_DCL_I			s
	NEW_GENUS_DCL_I			s	  -- s names a genus

	COMMUNITY_DCL_I			s
	NEW_TRANSPARENT_COMMUNITY_DCL_I s
	NEW_OPAQUE_COMMUNITY_DCL_I	s	  -- s names a community
	
These instructions should be preceded by a label instruction.  In the
internal form, the declaration is replaced by the index in the
class table of the thing that is declared.

=========================================================================
			RELATE AND MEET DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

The species/family hierarchy is described by relate declarations.
The form is as follows.

	(1) A byte containing RELATE_DCL_I.

	(2) 3 bytes containing the label of A, as a genus or
            community.

	(3) 3 bytes containing the label of B, as a genus
            or community.

A is declared to be less than B in the hierarchy.

This declaration has no internal form.

Meet declarations indicate intersections.  A meet declaration has
the form

	(1) a byte holding MEET_DCL_I

	(2) 3 bytes containing the label of A (as a genus
            or community).

	(3) 3 bytes containing the label of B (as a genus
            or community).

	(4) 3 bytes containing the label of C (as a genus or
            community or species or family). 
	    (If C is a pair, then this is a TYPE_DCL_I for PAIR@.)

This indicates that the intersection of A and B is C.

Ahead meet declarations are similar to meet declarations except
that the first byte contains AHEAD_MEET_DCL_I, and the meet is
marked as ahead.  The following asserts that the meet of A and B is C,
but does not require that A, B or C exist yet.

	(1) a byte holding AHEAD_MEET_DCL_I

	(2) 3 bytes containing the label of identifier A.

	(3) 3 bytes containing the label of identifier B.

	(4) 3 bytes containing the label of identifier C.
	    (If C is a pair, then the identifier is PAIR@.)

=========================================================================
			DEFAULT DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

Instruction DEFAULT_DCL_I defines a default for a genus or community.
Its form is

	(1) DEFAULT_DCL_I

	(2) 3 bytes containing the label of A, as a genus or
            community.

	(3) 1 byte holding 1 if this default is done after the
	    extension where A was created and 0 if it is done
	    in the extension where A was created.

	(4) Instructions that generate the type B.  

        (5) END_LET_I.

This does declaration Default A => B.  If there are no instructions
in part (4), then erase the default for A.


=========================================================================
			IMPORT DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

If s is the path name of a file, then 

	IMPORT_I s

causes file s to be imported.  This instruction has no internal form.
In s, $ stands for the directory where standard packages are put.

=========================================================================
			IRREGULAR DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

An irregular declaration consists of

	(1) An IRREGULAR_DCL_I instruction byte

	(2) A global label (the label of an identifier)

	(3) Instructions that build a type

	(4) An END_LET_I byte.

It indicates that the given identifier is irregular for the given type.

=========================================================================
			EXECUTE DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

An execute declaration consists of 

	(1) An EXECUTE_I or HIDDEN_EXECUTE_I instruction.  (HIDDEN_EXECUTE_I
            is used for an execute that is done but hidden from the
            debugger.)

	(2) A byte holding the index in env_size of the number of globals
	    to be used.

	(3) A sequence of global environment building instructions, which
	    build the global environment for the code of part (6).

	(4) A STOP_G_I instruction.

	(5) A byte holding the index in env_size of the number of 
	    local ids needed by the code in part (6).

	(6) The code to be executed, which should return via a RETURN_I 
	    instruction.

	(7) An END_I instruction.

The code of part (6) is saved for later execution, after all of
the packages have been read in.

In the internal format, the environment size byte following 
STOP_G_I is replaced by a three-byte environment descriptor number
that tells how to determine the names of identifiers used in
the executable part.

=========================================================================
			EXCEPTION DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

An exception declaration consists of a EXCEPTION_DCL_I instruction 
followed by 

  (1) A byte that contains 1 if the exception is trapped, and 0
     if the exception is not trapped.

  (2) A null-terminated string that is the name of the exception.

  (3) A three-byte number n, followed by a null-terminated 
      description string of length n.  If n is 0, there is 
      no following string.

  (4) A type, followed by an END_LET_I instruction.

The type is the type that occurs after the name in the 
exception-declaration in the source code.  It is () if none is
given.  

The name is forced to have the package name in front of it, 
followed by a slash, to prevent name conflicts.  So an exception called
exc defined in the export part of package p will have its name in part
(2) written p/exc.  If exc is local to the body of package p, the name
in part (2) will be p/p:exname.

This declaration has no internal form.

=========================================================================
			DEFINE DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

Each define declaration consists of 

	(1) A byte containing DEFINE_DCL_I.

 	(2) 3 bytes holding the global label of the identifier X being defined.

	(3) The mode of this declaration (one byte).

 	(4) A sequence of type construction instructions that leave the 
	    type of X on the type stack.  

        (5) Possibly an END_LET_I instruction, followed by a sequence
	    of type building instructions.  Can have as many of these as
	    desired.  X will be defined for each of these types.

	(6) An ENTER_I instruction.

	(7) A byte holding the index in env_size of the number of globals
	    to be defined in step (8).

	(8) A sequence of global environment building instructions.

	(9) A STOP_G_I instruction.

	(10) A byte holding the index in env_size of the number of locals 
	     needed to evaluate the identifier.

	(11) The code to evaluate the global identifier.

	(12) An END_I instruction

In the internal format, the code begins at part (4).  The environment size 
byte following STOP_G_I is followed by a three-byte environment descriptor 
number.


=========================================================================
			BEGIN-IMPLEMENTATION DECLARATIONS
=========================================================================

A package can contain parts that came from an interface package and
parts that came from an implementation package.  BEGIN_IMPLEMENTATION_I
is placed at the boundary between the two, so that the package reader
can know where declarations are coming from.

The BEGIN_IMPLEMENTATION_I instruction has no internal form.


#########################################################################
			GLOBAL ENVIRONMENT INSTRUCTIONS
#########################################################################

The global environment is built by type construction instructions and the
following instructions. When the global environment building instructions are
started, the type of the identifier being defined is sitting on the type stack.

Initially, the environment is empty.  Each GET_GLOBAL_I and TYPE_ONLY_I
instruction adds a value to the environment.  t is the top of the type stack.  

GET_GLOBAL_I(c) Pop t.  Let X be the entity identifier declared at
		global label c.  Store a reference to X, of type t, 
		in the next open cell of the environment that is being built. 

TYPE_ONLY_I	Like GET_GLOBAL_I, but puts the type t in the environment
		without any entity.


#########################################################################
			TYPE CONSTRUCTION INSTRUCTIONS
#########################################################################

In the following, x is a one byte integer, and c is a 3 byte label.
t is the top of the type stack, and tt is the next below the top.

STAND_T_I(x)	Push standard species or family T onto the type stack,
		where T is the species or family whose std_num is x.
		For example, if x is the std_num value of species 
		Natural, then this instruction pushes Natural onto 
		the type stack.

STAND_WRAP_T_I(x)  Push G where G is the standard
		   genus or community with std_num x.

STAND_VAR_T_I(x) Push a variable for standard genus or community number x.
		 (x is the std_num field.)

STAND_PRIMARY_VAR_T_I(x) Push a variable G`*a, where G is the
                      genus or community with standard number x.

STAND_WRAP_VAR_T_I(x) Push a variable G``a, where G is the
                      genus or community with standard number x.

TYPE_ID_T_I(c)	Push the species or family whose name is
		found at global label c.

WRAP_TYPE_ID_T_I(c) Push species G where G is the genus or
		    community that is found at global label c.

TYPE_VAR_T_I(c) Push a type or family variable whose genus or 
		community's name is at global label c.  c = 0 for a type
		variable over ANY.

PRIMARY_TYPE_VAR_T_I(c) Push a variable G`*a, where G is the genus or
		     community found at global label c.

WRAP_TYPE_VAR_T_I(c) Push a variable G``a, where G is the genus or
		     community found at global label c.

SECONDARY_DEFAULT_T_I Mark the variable on the top of the stack as
		      preferring a secondary default.

FUNCTION_T_I	Pop t and tt, and push (tt -> t).

PAIR_T_I	Pop t and tt, and push (tt, t).

LIST_T_I	Pop t and push List(t).

BOX_T_I		Pop t and push Box(t).

FAM_MEM_T_I	Pop t and tt, where t is a family F.  Push F(tt).

CONSTRAIN_T_I	Pop t and tt.  Add constraint tt >= t.

UNPAIR_T_I	Pop t, which must be either (a, b), or (a -> b) or
		b(a). Push a then b, so that b is on top.

HEAD_T_I	Pop t, which must be either (a,b) or (a->b) or b(a).
		Push a.

TAIL_T_I	Pop t, which must be either (a,b) or (a->b) or b(a).
		Push b.

POP_T_I		Pop t, and throw it away.

SWAP_T_I	Swap the two types on top of the type stack.

CLEAR_STORAGE_T_I Clear the type storage.

STORE_T_I	Pop t, and store it in the next available location in the
		type storage.

STORE_AND_LEAVE_T_I Same as STORE_T_I followed by a get on the same var.

GET_T_I(x)	Push the contents of location x in the type storage.

GLOBAL_FETCH_T_I(x)	Push the type at offset x in the global environment
			onto the type stack.


#########################################################################
			EXECUTABLE INSTRUCTIONS
#########################################################################


These instructions are executed in the body of functions and
execute declarations.  Each instruction has a one-byte code, 
possibly followed by one or two arguments.  Arguments called 
c have 3 bytes, and those called x, y and n have one byte.  

In the following, s is the top of the stack, ss is the next member down.

Each local label number is replaced, in the internal form, by the
offset (positive or negative) from the start of the instruction of
the byte referred to by that label.

=========================================================================
			STACK MANIPULATION
=========================================================================

DUP_I		Duplicate the top of the stack.  (I.e., pop t and push t
		twice.)

POP_I		Pop s, and throw it away.

SWAP_I		Swap s and ss.

LOCK_TEMP_I	Pop s, and put it into a temporary location.  Begin an
		atomic unit of code.  There is only one temporary location.

GET_TEMP_I	Push the value of the temporary location, and end the atomic
		unit.

=========================================================================
			BOXES, PLACES
=========================================================================

EMPTY_BOX_I	Pop s.  If s is empty, push true, else push false.  s can
		be a box or a place.

BOX_I		Create a new empty box, and place it on the stack.

PLACE_I   	Push a new empty place.

ASSIGN_I	Pop s and ss.  Assign entity s to box ss.

ASSIGN_INIT_I	Pop s and ss.  Assign entity s to box ss in the initial state.

ASSIGN_NODEMON_I Pop s and ss.  Assign s to box ss.  Do not call any
		 demon functions associated with box ss.

MAKE_EMPTY_I	Pop s, and force box s to be empty.

MAKE_EMPTY_NODEMON_I	Pop s, and force box s to be empty.  Do not run
			the demon for box s, if it exists.


=========================================================================
			OTHER CONSTANTS
=========================================================================

SMALL_INT_I(x)	Push integer x.

CHAR_I(x)	Push character x.  (Same as SMALL_INT_I.)

CONST_I(c)      Push the constant at label c.

ZERO_I		Push 0.

HERMIT_I	Push the hermit.

TRUE_I		Push true.

STD_BOX_I(x)	Push box x.

==========================================================================
			NUMBERS
==========================================================================

INT_DIVIDE_I	Pop s and ss, which must be integers.  Push the pair 
		(q,r) of quotient and remainder
		when ss is divided by s, with r on top.

AS_I(x)		x is the offset in the global env of the type of
		A -> B, where A is the type of ss.  Pop s and ss.  
		Push ss converted to type B.  


==========================================================================
			BOOLEAN AND COMPARISON
==========================================================================

NOT_I		Pop s and push not(s).

EQ_I		Pop s and ss.  Push ss == s.  s must be a string, a
		number or a box.

TEST_I(x)	Pop s.  Fail(x) if s is false.

ENUM_CHECK_I(k) If s >= k or s < 0 then fails with exception CONVERSION_EX.
		Otherwise no effect -- leaves the stack unchanged.

LONG_ENUM_CHECK_I(kk) Same as ENUM_CHECK_I, but kk is a long (3 byte) integer.

=========================================================================
			CARTESIAN PRODUCTS AND LISTS
=========================================================================

NIL_I		Push an empty list.

NILQ_I		Pop s, and push true just when s is nil.

PAIR_I		Pop s and ss, and push pair (ss,s).  This instruction also
		pushes ss::s.

MULTIPAIR_I(x)	Perform x consecutive PAIR_I instructions.

HEAD_I		Pop s, and push its first component.  If s is nil, then
		fail with exception emptyListX.

TAIL_I		Pop s, and push its second component.  If s is nil, then
		fail with exception emptyListX.

LEFT_I		Pop s, and push its first component.  If s is an
		unprotected unknown, then split it into a pair first.
		So this is an aggressive operation.

RIGHT_I		Pop s, and push its second component.  If s is an
		unprotected unknown, then split it into a pair first.
		So this is an aggressive operation.

MULTI_RIGHT_I(x) Perform x consecutive RIGHT_I instructions.

SPLIT_I		Pop s, which should be (a,b).  Push a then b, leaving b on
		top.  If s is nil, then fail with exception 0.

NONNIL_TEST_I   Fail(0) if s is nil.

SUBSCRIPT_I	Pop s and ss.  Push ss # s.

SUBLIST_I	Pop s and ss.  Push ss ## s.


=========================================================================
			FUNCTIONS AND APPLICATION
=========================================================================

FUNCTION_I(x) 	Place a function on the stack, with body just following the
		current instruction.  Continue execution at local label x.
		This instruction is followed by:

		  (1) A sequence of type-building instructions, terminated by
		      END_LET_I, that place the result type of the function 
		      on the type stack.  (In the internal representation, 
		      these instructions are replaced by an index in
		      lazy_type_instrs of the type-building code.)

		  (2) The body, consisting of a byte holding the index 
		      in env_size of the number of local ids that this 
		      function needs, followed by the executable code 
		      for the function.  The function should finish with 
		      a RETURN_I instruction.  The code will be started
		      with the actual parameter on the stack, and the 
		      result should be left on the stack.  In the internal
		      form, the environment size byte is followed by three
		      bytes holding the environment descriptor number.

REV_APPLY_I		Pop s.  Apply function s to argument 
			ss and leave result on the stack.

REV_PAIR_APPLY_I(x) 	Same as x PAIR_I instructions followed by REV_APPLY_I.

REV_TAIL_APPLY_I     	Same as REV_APPLY_I, but tail recursive.

REV_PAIR_TAIL_APPLY_I(x)  Same as x PAIR_I instructions followed by 
			  REV_TAIL_APPLY_I.

QEQ_APPLY_I		Apply an equality testing function that was
			created for a free coproduct type or family.
			s is the function, and ss and sss (one down from ss)
			are the parameters.  The equality tester would get
			the correct answer in all cases, so we could just
			do a REV_PAIR_APPLY_I instruction.  But, when either of
			ss and sss has tag NOREF_TAG, which is expected to
			be common, the equality test can be done more
			efficiently by comparing representations.

SHORT_APPLY_I		Apply ss to s, but with time limited to 
			SHORT_APPLY_TIME.  Push the result onto the
			stack after popping s and ss.  If the function
			application times out, then push a lazy entity.
			
RETURN_I		Return from a function or deferred expression.

INVISIBLE_RETURN_I	Return from a standard function.

=========================================================================
			GLOBAL ENVIRONMENT
=========================================================================

DYN_FETCH_GLOBAL_I(c) Like GET_GLOBAL_I, but puts result on stack instead
		  of environment.  In the internal form, the label c
		  is replaced by the offset in ent_names, as a three
		  byte integer.

G_FETCH_I(x)	  Push the value in location x of the current global 
		  environment.  The global environment is the outermost one.

GLOBAL_ID_VAL_I(x) x is the offset in the global environment of the type 
		   (String->t) of this instance of outerIdVal.  Pop s
		   and push the value of the global id whose name is s 
		   and whose type is t.

=========================================================================
			 LOCAL ENVIRONMENT
=========================================================================

FETCH_I(x)	Push the value found in the local environment at offset x.

LONG_FETCH_I(x,y) Push the value in location x of frame y from the top of the
		current environment.  (y would be 0 to be equivalent to a
		FETCH_I instruction.)

FINAL_FETCH_I(x) Similar to FETCH_I, but this is the last fetch of x.  If
		 there are no other refs to x, then drop the reference to
		 x.

FINAL_LONG_FETCH_I(x,y) Composite of LONG_FETCH_I and FINAL_FETCH_I.

EXIT_SCOPE_I(n)	Set the current environment to have only n bindings (0..n-1).

END_LET_I	See below.

Instructions LET_I, DEF_I, LET_AND_LEAVE_I, FINAL_LET_AND_LEAVE_I and
DEAD_LET_I are each followed by 
	(1) A null-terminated name,
	(2) A sequence of type-building instructions
	(3) An END_LET_I instruction
The name is the name of the environment field that is being bound.
The type building instructions build the type of this field, and are
assumed to be executed in this environment.  In internal format, a DEF_I
has its type building instructions replaced by an index in 
lazy_type_instrs.

In the internal form, only the offset information (x) is stored
with the instruction.  The other information is used in setting
up environment descriptors.

LET_I(x)	Pop s.  Place s into the current local environment at offset
		x.

LET_AND_LEAVE_I(x) Similar to LET_I, but leave the stack unchanged.

FINAL_LET_AND_LEAVE_I(x) Similar to LET_AND_LEAVE_I, but this the last
			 use of x.  Normally, don't store x.

DEAD_LET_I(x)   Similar to LET_I, but do nothing when do_tro is true.
		(Used for an identifier that is defined but not used.)

RELET_I(x)      Same as LET_I(x), but not followed by extra info.  This
                instruction is converted to a LET_I in package.c, so the
                evaluator in evaluate.c does not see it.  It has no
		internal form.

RELET_AND_LEAVE_I(x) Same as LET_AND_LEAVE_I, but not followed by extra
                     info. This instruction is converted to LET_AND_LEAVE_I
                     in package.c, so the evaluator does not see it -- it
		     has no internal form.

FINAL_RELET_AND_LEAVE_I(x) Same as FINAL_LET_AND_LEAVE_I, but not followed
                           by extra info.  This instruction is converted
                           to FINAL_LET_AND_LEAVE_I in package.c, so
                           it is not seen by the evaluator.  It has no
			   internal form.

DEF_I(y,x)	The code following this instruction is code to evaluate the
		identifier at offset x.  It starts with
		a byte holding the index in env_size of the number of local
		ids needed, and in internal format is followed by a 3-byte
		index of an environment descriptor.
		Define this id, and continue at local label y.

TEAM_I(x,y)	Following this instruction should be x DEF_I instructions,
		defining ids y, y+1, ..., y+x-1 in the local frame.  (This
		instruction suppresses environment ref counting and copying
		that would be incorrect for a team.)

=========================================================================
			CONDITIONALS AND LABELS
=========================================================================

GOTO_I(x)	Jump to local label x.

PAIR_GOTO_I(x,y) Do y PAIR_I instructions followed by GOTO_I(x).

GOTO_IF_FALSE_I(x) Pop the stack, and jump to local label x if the popped 
		   value is false.  Similar to GOTO_IF_NIL_I, but 
		   pops stack.

GOTO_IF_NIL_I(x) Goto local label x if s = nil.  Do not pop the stack.

AND_SKIP_I(x)	If s is false, leave s on the stack and goto local
		label x.  If s is true, then pop s and continue with
		the next instruction.

OR_SKIP_I(x)	If s is true, leave s on the stack and goto local label 
		x.  If s is false, then pop s and continue with the
		next instruction.

LLABEL_I(x)	Label this instruction by local label x.  Local labels are
		only in effect for one declaration.  This instruction has
		no internal form.

LONG_LLABEL_I(x) This instruction precedes another instruction that contains
                 a local label.  It indicates that the local label y that
		 occurs in the following instruction is to be considered
		 an extended local label (x,y).  This allows more
		 local labels.  This instruction can precede any instruction
		 that contains a local label, including LLABEL_I.
		 This instruction has no internal form.

TRY_I(x,k)	Place a TRY frame into the state, with else address 
		at local label x.  k is a single byte that tells what
		kind of try this is.  It is one of the following.
		   TRY_F	 try
		   TRYEACH_F	 try catchingEachThread
		   TRYTERM_F	 try catchingAllExceptions
		   TRYEACHTERM_F try catchingEachThread catchingAllExceptions

QUICK_TRY_I(x)	Like TRY_I, but is faster, and can only be used when the
		condition only has instructions that have local effects
		whose effect on the stack is monitored in evaluate.
		The else part begins at local label x.  The kind is
		always like a TRY_I(TRY_F).

THEN_I		Scan the control backwards to the first TRY frame, and 
		delete it.  The action depends on the kind of TRY
		frame.

=========================================================================
			STREAMS AND FAILURE
=========================================================================

STREAM_I(x)	Push a branch point with address at local label x.

MIX_I(x)	Fork the current activation with a similar one that
		begins at local label x.  

CHOOSE_MIX_I(x) Similar to MIX_I, but fork an activation for a
		choose one mixed instruction guard.

FAIL_I		Pop s.  Fail with exception s.

FAILC_I(x)	Fail with exception x.

PUSH_EXC_I	Push the current exception value onto the exception stack
		of the current activation.

POP_EXC_I	Pop the exception stack of the current activation.

EXCEPTION_I	Push the current exception.

Each of the following instructions has a global label in the external form, 
which is replaced by a single byte in the internal form.  That byte holds
the number of the exception.

EXC_CONST_I(c)  Push the exception whose number is at global label c.

EXC_WRAP_I(c)   Pop s, and push s wrapped with the exception number that
		is at global label c.

EXC_UNWRAP_I(c) Pop s.  If s is a qwrapped-value that is wrapped with the
		exception that occurs at global label c, then push
		the unwrapped value.  Otherwise fail with exception
		TEST_EX.

EXC_TEST_I(c)   Pop s.  If s is a qwrapped-value that is wrapped with the
		exception that occurs at global label c, then push
		true.  Otherwise push false.


=========================================================================
			CUTTING AND PRESERVING
=========================================================================

BEGIN_CUT_I	Push a mark frame onto the state.  This is done at the 
		beginning of a CutHere block.

END_CUT_I	Placed at the end of a CutHere block.  Scan the state back to 
		the first mark, destructively removing branch
		nodes and coalescing box tables.

CUT_I		Pop the stack.  (The stack should contain () on its top.)
		Perform a cut.  Nothing is pushed back onto the stack.

BEGIN_PRESERVE_I Push a mark frame onto the state.  This is done at the
		 beginning of a preserve block.

END_PRESERVE_I	Restore state 


=========================================================================
			TRAPPING
=========================================================================

PUSH_TRAP_I	Push a new trap node onto the trap list of the current 
		activation

POP_TRAP_I	Pop a node from the trap list of the current activation.

TRAP_I		Set the trap bit for the exception on the stack (s), in the
		top vector of the current activation.  Pop s.

UNTRAP_I	Clear the trap bit for the exception on the stack (s), in the
		top vector of the current activation.  Pop s.

ALL_TRAP_I	Push a value  so that
			ALL_TRAP_I
			TRAP_I
		will cause all exceptions to be trapped, and
			ALL_TRAP_I
			UNTRAP_I
		will cause all exceptions to be untrapped.


=========================================================================
			THREADS
=========================================================================

PAUSE_I
  Pop the stack, which should have () on its top.
  If there is a coroutine to run, switch to one, putting the current coroutine
  into the done list.  Otherwise, time out.

REPAUSE_I
  Similar to PAUSE_I, but a Repause.  It indicates that no progress has
  been made since the most recent pause! by this thread.

BEGIN_ATOMIC_I  Start an atomic section of code.  Don't time-out or
		switch to another coroutine until END_ATOMIC_I is
		executed.

END_ATOMIC_I	end an atomic section of code.


=========================================================================
			UNKNOWNS
=========================================================================

NONNIL_FORCE_I	Like NONNIL_TEST_I, but if s is an unknown, then force
		it to be nil.

NIL_FORCE_I	Fail(0) is s is not nil.  If s is an unknown, then
		force it to be nil.

BIND_UNKNOWN_I(x) Bind unknown s to object ss, and pop both.  

		  If x is 0 then s is unprotected, and s is bound to ss.
		  If x is 1, then s is protected and has the form 
		  (u,k), where u is the unknown and k is the write-key.  

=========================================================================
			LAZY EVALUATION
=========================================================================

TEST_LAZY_I,
TEST_LAZY1_I	Pop s from the stack and push false if s is lazy, true 
		if not.  Exception: every once in a while, TEST_LAZY1_I 
		will push false even when s is not lazy.

Each of the following instructions is followed by an END_LET_I-terminated
sequence of instructions that place the type of the lazily-computed result
on the top of the type stack.  In internal format, those instructions are
replaced by an index in lazy_type_instrs of the type instructions.  The code
following each instruction begins with a one-byte index in env_size of the
number of locals needed.  In the internal format, that byte is followed by
a three byte environment descriptor number.

LAZY_I(x)	Package the following code (which begins result-type building
		instructions and an index in env_size of the number of 
		locals needed) into a lazy expr, push it on the stack, 
		and continue at local label x.

LAZY_RECOMPUTE_I(x) Similar to LAZY_I, but calls for recomputation of
		    the result rather than storing it.

LAZY_LIST_I(x)	Begin a lazy list.  The current process resumes
		at local label x.  Code following this instruction has 
		result-type building instructions followed by the
		index in env_size of the number of locals needed,
		and the executable code of the lazy list generation expr.

LAZY_LIST_RECOMPUTE_I(x) Similar to LAZY_LIST_I, but calls for recomputatio
			 of the result rather than storing it.

=========================================================================
			DEBUGGING
=========================================================================

NAME_I(c)		Install the name of the global id at global label 
			c as the name of this piece of code.  In the
			internal form, c is replaced by the index
			in ent_names of the identifier at label c.  

SNAME_I(c)		Install the string at global label c as the name 
			of this piece of code.  In the internal form,
			c is replaced by the index in the constant
			table of the string declared at label c.

			The constant table must have a CSTR_TAG string
			for this string.

=========================================================================
			WRAP, UNWRAP
=========================================================================

GET_TYPE_I(x)	x is the offset in the global id table of the type A -> ()
		Pop s, push (), and push type A onto the type stack.

WRAP_I		Pop s, and pop t from type stack.  Push wrapped entity
		<<s:t>>.

UNWRAP_I	Pop wrapped entity <<s:T>>.  Push s onto the entity stack
		and T onto the type stack.

QWRAP_I(x)	Pop s and push quasi-wrapped entity (s:x). (the tag is x).

QTEST_I(x)	Pop s and push true if s has tag s, false otherwise.

QUNWRAP_I(x)	Pop s.  If s = (s':x), then push s'.  Otherwise fail with
		exception TEST_EX.  x mut be an integer tag.

UNIFY_T_I	Pop t1 and t2 from type stack and unify them.  If
		unification succeeds, do nothing.  If unification 
		fails, fail with exception SPECIES_EX.

=========================================================================
			COROUTINES
=========================================================================

COROUTINE_I(l,k) 
  Set offset k = Indirect(NOTHING) in current env.  Push coroutine immediately
  following onto done list of current activation.  
  COROUTINE_I instructions must occur in pairs, as follows.

    COROUTINE_I(l1,k1)
    --code for first coroutine
    RESUME_I
    LLABEL_I l1
    COROUTINE_I(l2,k2)
    --code for second coroutine
    LLABEL_I l2
    RESUME_I
    --code for continuing after both coroutines have finished.

  Both coroutine instructions are processed when the first is encountered.

RESUME_I
  Like PAUSE_I, but does not push current coroutine back -- terminates
  current coroutine.

CHECK_DONE_I(k)
  If offset k does not hold Indirect(NOTHING), do a return, else do nothing.

STORE_INDIRECT_I(k)
  Pop s and store s at the end of an indirection chain in the
  current environment at offset k.

=========================================================================
			MISC
=========================================================================

SPECIES_AS_VAL_I	Pop the top of the type stack, and push it back
			onto the entity stack as a value.

PUSH_TYPE_BINDINGS_I	Push the top of the_act.type_binding_lists
			onto the_act.type_binding_lists.  If 
			the_act.type_binding_list is NIL, then push NIL.
			This is used to enter a new type binding scope.

POP_TYPE_BINDINGS_I	Pop the_act.type_binding_lists.  This is used
			to exit a type binding scope.

COMMIT_TYPE_BINDING_I	Delete the member of the_act.type_binding_lists
			that is just below the top member.  This 
			commits to the changes made since the last 
			PUSH_TYPE_BINDINGS_I instruction.

TOPFORCE_I     Pop s.  Push s, evaluated to its top level.

LAZY_DOLLAR_I  Pop s.  If s is a lazy value and currently doing a
	       show!, the push a string describing lazy value s.  Otherwise
	       fail with exception TEST_EX.

STRING_DOLLAR_I Pop s, which is a string, and push back a string which
		is s with quote marks around it, and internal quotes
		and backslashes escaped.

BEGIN_VIEW_I	Set the state so that $ does not evaluate lazy parts.

END_VIEW_I	Undoes BEGIN_VIEW_I change.

RAW_SHOW_I	Print the representation of s on file ss.

LINE_I(x)	The following code is from line x of the source program.

FPRINT_I	Pop s and ss.  Print s on file ss.  ss must be an
		external file.

FPRINTLN_I	Pop s and ss.  Print s followed by a newline on file
		ss.  ss must be an external file.


=========================================================================
			OPERATIONS THAT FOLLOW PREFIXES
=========================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------------
			UNARY_PREF_I
------------------------------------------------------------------

Each of the following takes one parameter s on the stack.  Before
starting the instruction, s is fully evaluated.

*************** Operations on boxes ***********************

CONTENT_STDF	Pop s (a box or place), and push its content.  Fail with 
		exception EMPTY_BOX_EX if the box or place is empty.

CONTENT_TEST_STDF Pop s (a box or place), and push its content.  Fail with 
		exception TEST_EX if the box or place is empty.

PRCONTENT_STDF  Pop s (a box or place) and push its content.  If box
		s is empty, push NOTHING.

MAKE_ARRAY_STDF Pop s, and push an array of s empty boxes.

MAKE_PARRAY_STDF Pop s, and push a place array of size s.

RANK_BOX_STDF	Pop s (a box or place), and push its rank.

FLAVOR_STDF	Pop s (a box or place) and push its flavor (shared or
		nonshared).

BOXFLAVOR_TO_STRING_STDF
		Pop s (a box flavor, either shared or nonshared) and
		push the name of s (either "shared" or "nonshared").

COPYFLAVOR_TO_STRING_STDF
		Pop s (a copy flavor (shared, nonshared or same)) and
		push the name of s ("shared", "nonshared" or "same").

****************** Operations on numbers *****************

ZEROP_STDF	Pop s, and push true of s == 0, false otherwise.

NEGATE_STDF	Pop s and push -s.

SQRT_STDF	Pop s.  Push sqrt(s), to normal precision.

FLOOR_STDF	Pop s.  Push floor(s).

PULLAPARTREAL_STDF Pop s.  Push pair (m,e), where s = m*base^e is
                the internal representation of real number s.  m and
                e are both integers.

CEILING_STDF	Pop s.  Push ceiling(s).

NATURAL_STDF	Pop s.  Push it back (minus a type tag if there was
	        one), provided it is nonnegative.  Fail if negative.

INTEGER_STDF	Pop s,  Push an integer equivalant of s.  This converts
		from INTEGER`a to Integer, possibly by removing a type
		tag.

RATIONAL_STDF	Pop s, and push a rational equivalent of s.

REAL_STDF	Pop s.  Push s as a real number.

ABS_STDF	Pop s, and push its absolute value.

RECIPROCAL_STDF Pop s, and push 1/s.

MAKE_RAT1_STDF  Pop s, and push 1/s, as a rational number.  s is an integer.

ODD_STDF	Pop s, and push true if s is odd, false if s is even.

SIGN_STDF	Pop s, and push the sign of s (-1, 0 or 1).

PRED_STDF	If s > 0, pop s, and push s-1.  If s = 0, fail
		with exception domainEx("predecessor of 0");

EXP_STDF	Pop s, and push exp(s), to normal precision.

LN_STDF		Pop s, and push ln(s), to normal precision.

SIN_STDF	Pop s, and push sin(s), to normal precision.

INVTAN_STDF	Pop s, and push arctan(s), to normal precision.

STRING_TO_NAT_STDF Pop s (a string), and push the string that s represents.

STRING_TO_INT_STDF Pop s (a string), and push the integer that s represents.

STRING_TO_RAT_STDF Pop s (a string), and push the rational number that s
		   represents.

STRING_TO_REAL_STDF Pop s (a string), and push the real number that s 
		    represents.

********************** System functions *************************

FCLOSE_STDF          Pop s, and close outfile s.  Push ().

CHDIR_STDF	     Pop s, change the current directory to s, and push ().  
		     Fail with exception NO_FILE_EX if can't do that, and with
		     exception LIMIT_EX if s is too long.

GETENV_STDF	     Pop s, and return the value of environment variable
		     s.  Fail with exception DOMAIN_EX if there is no
		     such environment variable, and with exception
		     LIMIT_EX if s is too long.

DATE_STDF	     Pop (), and push a string describing the current
		     time and date.

SECONDS_STDF	     Pop (), and push the number of seconds since a reference
		     time.

FSTAT_STDF	     Perform fstat.  See system.ast.

RM_STDF		     Pop s, remove file s, and push ().
		     Fail with exception NO_FILE_EX if can't do that, and with
		     exception LIMIT_EX if s is too long.

RMDIR_STDF	     Pop s, remove directory s, and push ().
		     Fail with exception NO_FILE_EX if can't do that, and with
		     exception LIMIT_EX if s is too long.

MKDIR_STDF	     Pop s, make a directory called s, and push ().
		     Fail with exception NO_FILE_EX if can't do that, and with
		     exception LIMIT_EX if s is too long.

DIRLIST_STDF	    Pop s, and push a list of the names of all files
		    in directory s.

GETCWD_STDF	    Pop s, and push the current working directory,
		    a string.

FLUSH_FILE_STDF	    Pop s, which must be an outfile.  Flush its buffer.

OS_ENV_STDF	    Pop s, which must be (), and push a list of pairs
		    [(name1,val1), (name2,val2),...] that describe the
		    operating system environment.

*********************** General conversions to string ****************

TO_STRING1_STDF 	Pop s, and push $s, where s is number or function or
			box or place.

BOOL_TO_STRING_STDF	Pop boolean s, and push its string equivalent.

CHAR_TO_STRING_STDF 	Pop char s, and push its string equivalent.

HERMIT_TO_STRING_STDF 	Pop (), and push its string equivalent.

EXCEPTION_TO_STRING_STDF Pop exception s, and push its string equivalent.

COMPARISON_TO_STRING_STDF Pop Comparison value s, and push its string 
			  equivalent.

FILEMODE_TO_STRING_STDF  Pop FileMode value s, and push its name.

OUTFILE_DOLLAR_STDF  	Pop s, and push the name of outfile s.

SPECIES_DOLLAR_STDF	Pop s, which should be a value that is a species,
			and push a string that describes that species.

************************** Unknowns ******************************

PRIVATE_UNKNOWN_STDF	Pop s, and push a new nonshared, unprotected unknown.

PUBLIC_UNKNOWN_STDF	Pop s, and push a new shared, unprotected unknown.

PROT_PRIV_UNKNOWN_STDF	Pop s, and push a pair (u,k) where u is a new
			protected nonshared unknown, and k is its write-key.

PROT_PUB_UNKNOWN_STDF	Pop s, and push a pair (u,k), where u is a new
			protected shared unknown, and k is its write-key.

************************** Bit vectors ******************************

BV_MASK_STDF	     Pop s, and push a bit vector of s 1's (as an integer).

BV_MIN_STDF	     Pop s, which is an integer thought of as a bit
		     vector.  Push pair (k,v), where k is the index
		     from the right (starting with 0) of the first 1 bit in s,
		     and v is the result of setting that 1-bit to 0 in s. 

BV_MAX_STDF	     Pop s, which is an integer thought of as a bit
		     vector.  Push pair (k,v), where k is the index of
		     the leftmost 1-bit in s, and v is the result of
		     setting that 1-bit to 0.

************************** Misc ******************************

WILLTRAP_STDF        Pop s, and push true if exception s will be trapped,
		     and false if s will not be trapped.

FORCE_STDF	Pop s, and push the result of fully evaluating s.

PRIM_TRACE_STDF Turn on or off tracing.  Only used during debugging
		of the interpreter -- NOT A USER INSTRUCTION!.
		See evaluate/evaluate.c:prim_trace for what the
		argument means.

CONT_NAME_STDF	Pop (), and push the name of the continuation of the
		current function.

GET_STACK_DEPTH_STDF	Pop () and push the current depth of the run-time
			stack.

PROFILE_STDF    Pop s.  If s is true, turn on profiling.  If s is
		 false, turn off profiling.  Push ().

SET_STACK_LIMIT_STDF The interpreter keeps a soft limit on the number
		     of stack frames.  It queries the user if the stack
		     size exceeds the limit.  This instructions pops s, 
		     sets the stack limit to s, and pushes ().

GET_STACK_LIMIT_STDF Pop (), and push the current stack limit.

SET_HEAP_LIMIT_STDF  The interpreter keeps a soft limit on the number
		     of bytes used in the heap.  It queries the user if
		     the heap gets too large.  This instruction pops s,
		     sets the heap limit to s, and pushes ().

GET_HEAP_LIMIT_STDF  Pop (), and push the current heap limit.

SHOW_ENV_STDF	     Pop s, and print the current environment on file s.

SHOW_CONFIG_STDF     Pop s, and print the current configuration of file s.

LOAD_PACKAGE_STDF    Pop s, and load package s.  s is a string (the name of
		     the file containing the package.)

POSITION_STDF	     Pop s, and push its tag.  s must be a value
		     that is tagged by an integer, as is created by
		     a QWRAP_I instruction.

ACQUIRE_BOX_STDF     Pop s.  If s is a box, push (s,k), where k is 
		     true if s is a nonshared box, and false if s is a
		     shared box.  If s is not a box, then fail with
		     exception testX.

SUPPRESS_COMPACTIFY_STDF Pop s.  If s is true, turn off compactifying
			 in the garbage collector.  If s is false, then
			 turn on compactifying.  Note: What this really
			 does is add one to a counter if s is true, 
			 and subtract one if s is false (and the counter
			 is positive).  If the counter
			 is positive, then compactification is turned
			 off.  For each time compactification is
			 turned on, it should be turned off.

INTERN_STRING_STDF   Pop s, and push an equivalent string that has been
		     interned into the string table.



-----------------------------------------------------------
			BINARY_PREF_I
-----------------------------------------------------------

Each of the following instructions takes two parameters s and ss
on the stack.  Before evaluation of the instruction, both s and
ss are fully evaluated.

*********************** Numbers *****************************

PLUS_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss + s.

MINUS_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss - s.

ABSDIFF_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push |ss - s|.

TIMES_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss * s.

DIVIDE_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push s/ss, or fail if not possible. 

MAKE_RAT2_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss/s (a rational number).

TO_STRING2_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push the representation of ss as a string,
		using s as formatting information.  ss must be a number.

DIV_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss div s.

MOD_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss mod s.

GCD_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push gcd(s, ss).

POW_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss ^ s.  s must be an integer.

UPTO_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss upto s.

DOWNTO_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss downto s.

*************************** Comparisons ***********************

The following work for numbers.

COMPARE_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push compare(ss, s). 
			less    if ss < s
			equal   if ss = s
			greater if ss > s


LT_STDF		Pop s and ss.  Push ss < s (boolean).

LE_STDF		Pop s and ss.  Push ss <= s (boolean).

GT_STDF		Pop s and ss.  Push ss > s (boolean).

GE_STDF		Pop s and ss.  Push ss >= s (boolean).

NE_STDF		Pop s and ss.  Push ss =/= s (boolean).

************************* Bit vectors *************************

BV_AND_STDF	Pop s and ss, and push their bit-wise "and".

BV_OR_STDF	Pop s and ss, and push their bit-wise "or".

BV_XOR_STDF	Pop s and ss, and push their bit-wise "exclusive or".

BV_SHL_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push the result of shifting s to
		the left ss bits.

BV_SHR_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push the result of shifting s to
		the right ss bits.

BV_SETBITS_STDF	Pop s and ss.  ss is a bit vector, and s is a pair
		(l,k), where l is a list of natural numbers and
		k is either 0 or 1.  Push the vector that results from
		ss by setting the bits at indices given in list l to k.

BV_FIELD_STDF	Pop s and ss.  ss is a bit vector, and s is a pair
		(m,n) of integers.  Push the vector that results by
		shifting ss to the right m bits, and then taking
		the rightmost n bits.  (Padding on the left is with 0's.)

*********************** System **************************

RENAME_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Rename file s as ss.

INPUT_STDF	Pop s and ss, and push a list holding the content of the file 
		whose name is s, with mode given by list-of-modes ss.

FOPEN_STDF	Pop s and ss, and push the outfile named s, opened in
		mode ss, where ss is a list of file modes.

*********************** Boxes **************************

ONASSIGN_STDF	Process an onassign call.  See standard.ast.


-------------------------------------------------------
			LIST1_PREF_I
-------------------------------------------------------

Each of these instructions takes a single argument s on the
stack.  No evaluation of s is initially done.

LENGTH_STDF	Pop s.  Push the length of s.

REVERSE_STDF	Pop s.  Push the reversal of s.

PACK_STDF	Pop s, and push a packed version of s.

LAZY_LEFT_STDF	Pop s, and push lazyLeft(s).

LAZY_RIGHT_STDF	Pop s, and push lazyRight(s).

LAZY_HEAD_STDF	Pop s, and push lazyHead(s).

LAZY_TAIL_STDF	Pop s, and push lazyTail(s).


-------------------------------------------------------
			LIST2_PREF_I
-------------------------------------------------------

Each of these instructions takes two arguments s and ss on
the stack.  No evaluation of either is initially done.

APPEND_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push ss ++ s.

DOCMD_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push the output from command s (where s
		is a list of parts) with its standard input containing
		ss.

SCAN_FOR_STDF	Pop s and ss.  Push the result of scanForChar(s, ss).


-------------------------------------------------------
			TY_PREF_I
-------------------------------------------------------

Each of the following takes a single argument s on the stack, and 
additionally is told its own type. s is evaluated to its top level.

BOX_TO_STRING_I(x): Pop s and push a string description of s, which must be
		    a box or place.  x is the offset of the type of this
		    function.  It is used to put this box into a
		    table for print_rts.

WRAP_STDF		Pop s and push <<s:T>>, where T is the
			domain type of this function.

COMPAT_STDF	Pop s, which must be an ordered pair (a,b).  Both 
		a and b must be numbers.  Push a pair
		(a',b') where a' and b' are the same numbers as 
		a and b, respectively, but such that
		the types of a' and b' are the same.
		Conversion of types is upwards, in
		the direction Natural -> Integer -> Rational -> Real.
		Also push the type of a' and b' onto the
		type stack.

-------------------------------------------------------
			UNK_PREF_I
-------------------------------------------------------

UNKNOWNQ_STDF		Pop s, and push true if s is an unknown, false if s
			is not an unknown.

PROTECTED_UNKNOWNQ_STDF	Pop s, and push true if s is a protected unknown, 
			false if not.

UNPROTECTED_UNKNOWNQ_STDF Pop s, and push true if s is an unprotected unknown, 
			  false if not.

SAME_UNKNOWN_STDF	Pop s, which is a pair of unknowns.  Push true
			if the two unknowns are the same unknown, and
			false if not.
